# Pre-Production Audit Fix Plan

This plan details the exact fixes for the issues discovered during the code audit, covering both frontend React state/UX bugs and backend API validation gaps.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Please review the proposed changes. The plan includes migrating several Modals to use `React.lazy()` and `Suspense`, which will greatly improve your initial bundle size. It also adds a more robust loading state mechanism via an array of targeted loading IDs rather than a single boolean.

## Proposed Changes

### Frontend State Store Updates

#### [MODIFY] `useProjectStore.js`
- Update `fetchProjectById` to set `currentProject: null` and `loading: true` *before* the Axios request, preventing the visual ghosting of stale project data.
- Ensure `loading: false` is set in the `finally` block.

#### [MODIFY] `useTaskStore.js`
- Wrap `actionLoading: true/false` around `updateTaskStatus`, `assignTaskMembers`, and `unassignTaskMember` to prevent concurrent UI requests.
- Add an `optimisticUpdateTaskStatus` action to allow immediate UI responses without screen flickers.
- Add an `activeTaskActions` array state mapping specific `taskId`s to their loading state. This is a massive improvement over one global loading boolean, as it will only lock the specific task being deleted or updated, rather than the entire page of tasks.

### Frontend Page & Component Updates

#### [MODIFY] `ProjectsPage.jsx`
- Replace the aggressive `if (loading) return <Spinner />` logic that destroys the UI on re-fetch.
- The spinner will only map to `loading && projects.length === 0`.
- Add a subtle loading indicator (like a small spinner or opacity reduction) for background re-fetches when `projects.length > 0`.
- Add basic Skeleton loader structures for aesthetic appeal during first paints.

#### [MODIFY] `ProjectDetailsPage.jsx`
- Import all `Modal` components (`AssignTaskModal`, `EditTaskModal`, `ReassignMembersModal`, `EditProjectModal`, `InviteMemberModal`) using `React.lazy()` and wrap them in `<React.Suspense fallback={null}>`.
- Add `disabled={currentTaskLoading}` to the Delete, Status select, and Remove member buttons by reading the targeted `activeTaskActions` store array instead of a global boolean.
- Wire the Select dropdown status `onChange` to use a local optimistic UI update to avoid the native HTML snap-back flicker.
- Render skeleton loaders when `tasksLoading && tasks.length === 0`.

### Backend Controller Updates

#### [MODIFY] `projects.controller.js`
- Improve `updateProject`:
  - Check `if (!name.trim()) return next(new ErrorHandler("Project name cannot be empty", 400));` inside the `name !== undefined` block to prevent overwriting with whitespace or empty strings.

#### [MODIFY] `task.controller.js`
- Improve `updateTask`:
  - Enforce `title.trim()` truthiness so an update cannot submit an empty task title.

## Open Questions

None. These are standard best practices.

## Verification Plan

### Manual Verification
1. I will navigate from `/projects` to `Project A`, go back, and click `Project B`. I verify that `Project A`'s data does not incorrectly render for a second initially.
2. I will spam-click the task Delete button and ensure the disabled state applies immediately, preventing duplicate toast errors.
3. I will test changing a Task Status to ensure it flips smoothly without snapping back rapidly.
4. I will verify backend validation effectively blocks empty string inputs when updating tasks and projects.
